Comparing EQ and SWG isn't even apples and oranges. It's Jabba the Hutt's drool compared to Evian (or vice versa, depending on who you ask, and your own playstyle preferences). <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://img.villagephotos.com/p/2003-6/226776/BalmungSig2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jarnin>Jarnin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Likes to wear<BR>Yoda Under-Roos</span><br>  Posts: 2869<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/26/03 5:31 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ..</span><hr size=1> You want info? It's pretty basic really.<br>
<br>
You pick a race and a profession. A Profession is a collection of disciplines, and disciplines are groups of skills, abilities, or schematics.<br>
<br>
Skills = Character advancement; as this increases, so do your chances at performing abilities (percentage based). These are innate, and do not need to be activated.<br>
<br>
Abilities = Things your character can do, like mask their scent or do a body shot with a pistol. These are triggered, and need to be activated to work.<br>
<br>
Schematics = These are like crafting patterns in EQ, and allow you to build devices and items. You get these as you advance through a discipline, or from NPCs.<br>
<br>
So, by learning and advancing a discipline, you'll advance skills, learn new abilities, and have access to more complex schematics.<br>
<br>
<br>
So how do you gain experience? It's easy; just use your skills and abilities. You can earn 3 types of experience:<br>
<br>
Profession Experience: This exp you get for using your professional skills. For instance, you get combat exp for killing stuff, which can be used for a couple different disciplines from a couple different professions. It's not specific to any profession or disiciple.<br>
<br>
Specific Experience: This exp you get for using abilities or skills from a specific disipline. For instance you can only get trapping experience by successfully using a trap on a creature, but if that trap kills the creature, you'll also get combat experience.<br>
<br>
What about skill points? That's easy; you start with all you'll ever get. You get 250 skill points when you begin the game, and as you learn new skills and professions, you'll use up skill points.<br>
Starting professions cost the most, at 15 points each. Get all the professions to start with, and from there, just use the skills and abilities you like. That will show you what types of advanced professions you'll probably like, because you'll advance skills you enjoy doing, and the others you can just get rid of later.<br>
If you find that you don't use entire professions, then you can surrender those to, and get back any points you spent. So in the end, you can master 2.5 professions, or you can generalize across all 6.<br>
<br>
<br>
As for professions, there are 6 starting professions:<br>
<br>
Artisan: General Crafting &amp; Resource Collection<br>
Brawler: Melee Combat<br>
Entertainer: Mental Healing<br>
Marksman: Ranged Combat<br>
Medic: Physical Healing<br>
Scout: Exploring &amp; Animal Combat<br>
<br>
...There are 6 Hybrid Professions:<br>
<br>
Bio-Engineer: Creation of cloned animals for pets and resources<br>
Bounty Hunter: Special missions, moves and equipment<br>
Combat Medic: Combat based healer<br>
Commando: Special Unarmed &amp; Ranged combat abilities<br>
Smuggler: Spice Crafting &amp; Dirty Fighting techniques<br>
Squad Leader: Group Movement &amp; Combat bonuses<br>
<br>
...There are 21 Advanced Professions:<br>
<br>
Architect: Creation of buildings, structures &amp; Furniture<br>
Armorsmith: Creation of Armor &amp; And Armor powerups<br>
Carabineer: Carabine blaster specialist<br>
Chef: Food &amp; drink crafting specialist<br>
Creature Handler: Pet taming &amp; eventually mount creation<br>
Dancer: Entertainment Healer specializing in Dance<br>
Doctor: Medicine crafting &amp; Healing specialist<br>
Droid Engineer: Droid crafting for pets &amp; crafting stations<br>
Fencer: One handed sword specialist<br>
Image Designer: Character appearance customization<br>
Jedi: The unknown uber profession<br>
Merchant: Business owner &amp; NPC employee operator<br>
Musician: Entertainment Healer specializing in Music<br>
Pikeman: Melee combatant specializing in 2 handed blunt weapons<br>
Pistoleer: Range combatant specializing in pistols<br>
Ranger: Advanced Scouting &amp; Creature skills<br>
Rifleman: Range combatant specializing in rifles.<br>
Swordsman: Melee combatant specializing in two hande swords<br>
Tailor: Crafter specializing in clothing production<br>
Teras Kasi Artist: Melee combatant specializing in hand to hand combat<br>
Weaponsmith: Crafter specializing in weapon production<br>
<br>
<br>
Combat is pretty basic. You either run up to a target and start whacking on it with fists, blades, or poles, or you can stand back and shoot it with a pistol, carabine, or rifle. It's the same thing as EQ combat, you get special moves you can perform for more damage, but the cool thing is you can cue up moves in advance, so you can do some nifty combos.<br>
<br>
Weapons have a min/max damage rating, as well as refiring rate, and special move costs. When you do a special move, you'll use a little of your mind, action, or health pools depending on what move you use.<br>
<br>
Death is done really well. Most creatures aren't killers, and as soon as you're knocked out they will wander off. So when one of your pools (Health, Action, Mind) is reduced to 0, you're incapacitated, which means you fall on the ground and can't do anything for a minute or so. The good thing is you're not dead, so when you come to you can heal up and be right back in the action.<br>
<br>
Some NPCs and creatures will do a deathblow on you, which kills your character. Your options are then to respawn at the nearest cloning station (if you saved your cloning data), or spawning at a pre-arranged cloning station.<br>
<br>
If you do end up dying, you can save yourself a corpse run by insuring all your items, so when you die the items you insure will appear on your freshly cloned body. It costs money to insure your items, but not so much that it's painful. This saves you a corpse run, unless you had a bunch of uninsured items on your body, like looted items from NPCs or harvested resources.<br>
<br>
Pets are pretty cool. You either tame baby creatures that are out in the wild, you can buy one from a Bio-Engineer, or you can buy a droid from a droid engineer.<br>
Then you train the creature it's commands, or you program a droid. They have all the basic commands, like follow me, attack, and so on, but there are a couple new ones, like Patrol; which allows you to create a group of waypoints your pet will follow, like around your house or factory. You can also have your pets follow a friend around, and the pet will obey their commands. You can sell pets, and they'll obey the commands you taught them.<br>
In order to heal a pet, you can feed it, or change it's power battery if it's a robot. You can also have animals perform tricks to heal it's mind pool. Pets will let you know when they want to play.<br>
<br>
<br>
Banking is pretty simple, but a bit more complex than what you're probably used to in EQ. See, each city has a bank, which allows you to store your hard-earned credits, but you can only have an active safety deposit box at one bank at a time. A safety deposit box is where you store your items.<br>
So when you move from one planet to the next, you'll need to empty your safety deposit bank and move the stuff to the bank you want to join.<br>
You can access your credits at any bank no matter where you are.<br>
<br>
The bazaar system is well done in some ways and in others not so well done. For instance, there are bazaar terminals at every city in the game, and you can search any city on any planet from any bazaar terminal in the game. However, the list of items is truncated to save the database from blowing up, so you'll see items in alphabetical order for the most part.<br>
<br>
When you buy an item from the bazaar, you have to travel to retrieve the item from the place that you purchased it from, so if you're in Mos Eisly and you buy a turban from Theed on Naboo, you have to travel to Theed to pick up the turban. This is good and bad, in that you can secure items you want to buy, but you have to pay for tickets to get to the place you bought it from in order to pick it up.<br>
Oh, I forgot, there are two ways to sell things in SWG; Instant sales (X items for Y credits), or auctions. Auctions last as long as you set them for, but no longer than a week. People can bid on items and when the auction is over the money goes to your bank account.<br>
It costs money to put items on sale in the bazaar; basically a means to make NPC merchants a cheaper option, as well as keeping people from storing items in the bazaar.<br>
<br>
Missions are simple; find a mission terminal (usually near a spaceport or a guildhall) and you get your choice of destroy or delivery missions. This is how you'll make your credits as a noob. Delivery missions are simple; pickup an item and deliver it to another npc. These NPCs can be in the same town (lower reward) or another town on the same planet (higher reward). Just remember, planets are big, and tickets are pretty explensive as a noob. Running is dangerous. Take local missions until you can get the money for cloning, insuring and ticket costs.<br>
Destroy missions are a bit more straight forward; go here, and blow up either a creature lair or an NPC camp/outpost generator. The critters and NPCs guard the lair/generators, so doing these solo with low combat skills isn't advised.<br>
Once you've finished your mission, your reward is automatically placed in your bank account.<br>
Oh yeah, you can only take two missions at a time, but you can usually get them pretty close together if you take the time and are picky with which missions you accept.<br>
<br>
<br>
Well, thats the basics. If you have any more questions, shoot them out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whizbangdustyboots>Whizbang Dustyboots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder Arcanist<BR>Gnomus Originalus</span><br>  Posts: 13532<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/26/03 7:18 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> You're slipping, Whiz. Your next post regarding SW:G should include a return to the scathing insults and contempt for those who shipped a Star Wars game without player ships and sensible Jedi systems.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Eh, at this point, that opinion's gone mainstream, so belaboring the point would just be being a jackass for its own sake.<br>
